		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64448168" name="comment_link_64448168" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23311752&amp;cid=64448168" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64448168)" >Check your units [Re: Yay to the abolition of ...]</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64448168" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64448168); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Geoffrey.landis">Geoffrey.landis</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Geoffrey.landis">( 926948 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64448168"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64448168"><p><div class="quote"><p>The problem is that nobody is going to drive such a death trap.  Sodium releases 30x the energy as Lithium when it burns.</p></div><p>No it doesn't; less. Check your data. 416 kJ/mol for burning sodium, compared to 596 kJ/mol for lithium.</p><p>If it did have more energy, of course, it would be <b>vastly</b> better than lithium on a battery energy per unit weight basis. Unfortunately, it's not.</p><p>Sodium does ignite more easily, but that's cancelled out by the fact that really it's the electrolyte that's burning, and the electrolytes used for sodium batteries are <i>harder</i> to ignite.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64448168">

</div>
